New Results of Sweden ’ s Asylum Age Review Test
Recent results of tests for asylum seekers in Sweden, which have undergone a new method of medical assessment of their age, show that more than 80% of those tested are over 18 years of age, but not everyone believes in the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish Forensic Medicine Authority (Rättsmedicinalverket) started the testing last year.
During the asylum procedure, they are supposed to make the assessment of age more accurate after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migration Code) was criticised for errors in assessing the correct age of some refugees who were minors.
To date, migration net has sent 6,880 cases to be tested, and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now released the results of a total of 2,481 tests from mid-March to 31 July 2017.
Eighty per cent (2002) were considered 18 or older, while in another 25 cases the Forensic Medicine Agency assessed that the person was "possibly 18 years or older".
In 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person is' possibly under 18 years old '.
The tests are carried out only in cases where the age of the person is called into question.
According to Johan Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results have been consistent in recent months.
"We see no great difference in statistics of recent months, the numbers are quite constant," he said to the magazine The Local.
The high proportion of cases in which the person was judged to be over 18 years does not necessarily mean that the asylum seeker lied about his age.
In May, the Agency published the results of 581 tests and said that there were 442 cases' suggesting that the person being investigated was 18 years or older '.
When the Svenska Dagbladet investigated the 581 published results, she found that in 243 of these cases, the person had openly said that she would be 18 years old this year.
The method of medical age assessment, in which X-rays of wisdom teeth and MRI images of knee joints are taken, which are then analysed by dentists and radiologists, has also been criticised in a number of areas.
A skeptic is the endocrinologist Claude Marcus of the Karolinska Institute, whose work involves assessing the biological maturity of humans to see whether they passed through puberty sooner or later than usual.
"I had reason to think about it, and I do not believe that the type of measurement should be used.
Judging biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we cannot say it for sure, we should not act as if we could, "he said to the Metro newspaper.
However, Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency defended the accuracy of the tests: "In general, you can say that the risk of misjudging a child as an adult is low.
The biggest risk is when the person is under 18, in this case this is about 10%. '
