NHS (The National Health Service) is to prescribe controversial HIV drugs to 10,000 people.
Patients will have access to "transformational" HIV prevention treatment from September, following a battle before the High Court against the funding of the drug in the NHS.
NHS England announced that a pre-sex pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) that can reduce the risk of infection in high-risk patients by about 86% is now delivered by the health service through a first three-year study for estimated 10,000 people.
He agreed to finance the trial after the Court of Appeal confirmed last year a Supreme Court ruling that the NHS had the power to pay for the PrEP despite the claim that local authorities should fund it.
The move announced on Thursday was welcomed by NHS England boss Simon Stevens as "an important new intervention," while the National Aids Trust (NAT) called it a "decisive moment".
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool, and Sheffield will be among the first to allow people to register, and more clinics will follow in October, before it will be introduced across England in April 2018.
Preexposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a consequence of HIV drugs taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Studies have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV transmission in cases of infection.
Taking PrEP before intercourse means that there are just enough drugs in a person's body to prevent HIV infection.
Such drugs can be taken every day or two hours before sexual intercourse.
Those eligible for treatment include gay or bisexual men, transsexuals, and people with HIV-positive partners who have not been treated successfully.
In clinics, appropriate participants are identified who agree to the study, including men, women, transgenders, and individuals who have a partner whose HIV status is not known to be controlled by antiretroviral treatment.
People who live in England and are registered with a family doctor may also register to participate in their local participating sex clinic.
The program will be £10 million and NHS England signed a contract to deliver medicines this week after an international competitive procurement.
The study is intended to assess the full potential of PrEP by gathering clinical evidence on how it is targeted, recorded, and implemented on a large scale.
Stevens said: "This major new intervention should complement and surpass the far-reaching and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It is another milestone in more than three decades of progress in addressing one of humanity's greatest health challenges. '
Deborah Gold, Chief Executive at NAT (National Aids Trust), said: "This is a crucial moment in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, if targeted at vulnerable and vulnerable people, offers the opportunity to change the English HIV epidemic.
From September onwards, people at high risk of HIV will have access to this NHS-funded attempt in England to develop a new instrument that is truly individually controlled and not subject to negotiation with a partner, which will improve many, many lives.
We warmly welcome this announcement. '
Ian Green, chairman of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: "The priority must now be for the study to be carried out quickly across the country and for no one at risk of HIV to be left behind.
Now that PrEP testing has been obtained, we are on the way to protecting more than 10,000 people infected with HIV. '
Sharon Hodgson, Shadow Health Minister, said: 'The start of the PrEP process is welcome and overdue after months of delays and slow implementation by the government.
The evidence shows how transformational this drug can be as part of our approach to HIV prevention, and how it can stop transmission of this life-threatening infection.
This attempt brings us a step closer to understanding the advantages of PrEP.
It is now important that this study be carried out as quickly as possible throughout the country in order to protect people who are infected with HIV and that it will help us move a step closer to ending the spread of HIV in society '.
