Facebook wants to step up fact-checking in the fight against fake news
Facebook wants to send more potential articles with fake reports to third-party fact-checking agents, and then display their results under the original paper, the world ’ s largest online social network said Thursday, and is one of its efforts to fight so-called fake news.
The company said in a statement on its website that it will start using updated machine learning methods to identify possible false reports and send them to fact-auditors who may display the results of the fact-checking from the original article.
Facebook has been criticized as one of the main distribution points for so-called fake news, many of which believe that they also influenced the 2016 US presidential election.
The problem has become a major political issue in Europe, too, with French voters flooded with false stories in the run-up to the May presidential election, and Germany supports a plan to punish social media networks if they fail to quickly eliminate hateful postings, as they did before the September election.
On Thursday, Facebook said in a separate statement in German that a test of the new fact-checking will be launched in the US, France, the Netherlands, and Germany.
"Besides recognizing what stories are challenged by third-party fact-checking, people want more context to make informed decisions about what they read and share," said Sara Su, product manager for Facebook news in a blog.
She added that Facebook will continue to test its feature on the "related article" and work on other changes to its news feed to reduce fake news.
Making a comic novel: A Castle in the History of England
In his recent past, Scotney Castle was featured in a squeeze music video and was a loophole for Margaret Thatcher in the 1970s and 1980s.
But Scotney has lived 700 years of turbulent history from his cosy seat in the Bewll River Valley in Kent, and has now become an inspiration for a graphic novel by Jamie Rhodes, a mocphaarian Yorkshire madman with a penchant for historical documents.
"I find it so nice to look at the handwriting of someone who has been dead for 300 years," he says wistfully.
'What a personal relationship to keep this letter in my hands'.
A Castle in England spans the period from the Middle Ages to the age of Edward and documents the families who lived in Scotney.
It is not the first book from Rhodes based on an archive: he wrote in 2014 'Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories', a collection inspired by documents in the British Library - a project he unexpectedly found emotional.
"I only reacted to the thumb print on the side of a letter written by a double agent in the 1700's who worked for the Jacobins," he says.
"That is his thumbs!
And letters always smell smoke, because at that time a fire was lit because of the light.
For someone who lives 300 years later, the smell has an effect, as if it were there.
Oh, I love archives! '
For someone so beaten with old papers that he is supported by the National Trust and the Arts Council of England and lived in a castle for almost four months ("To be honest, I have a little overrated my welcome"), this all seems too good to be true.
Rhodes spent his days exploring the Victorian "new" castle, exploring the archives and exploring the many treasures and curiosities of the castle, such as the mounted hyena heads on the walls and the bottles that had spent centuries in the ditch.
He wandered through the grounds and ruins of the old castle and talked to landscape carers, gardeners and sometimes artists working on the illustrations of his book.
Then, at night he drank "whiskey and started to write".
The intimate story of Scotney is relatively unknown, as the National Trust won full access only in 2006, when the last heir, Elizabeth Hussey, died.
When Rhodes arrived a decade later, the employees just began to look after the archive that he described as "hundreds of years in which aristocrats said" Oh, throw it on the roof ".
diaries, letters from the time of the English Empire, maps depicting who owned what: "You might think that land conflicts would be boring," says Rhodes, "but there was a birch fighting for the two families.
Guys, let everything go his way! '
Some of the stories in the collection use the castle as a starting point for a broader exploration of English history, including The Labourer, who follows a man who leaves the newly built castle to join the peasant uprising of 1381.
"There is a record of a rebellion that occurred in the castle in 1380, in this book entitled 'Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex', says Rhodes.
"The peasant uprising began in this area and I thought an uprising was a good start.
Perhaps the two are linked? '
Other stories are deeply rooted in the history of the castle, such as The Priest, which tells the story of the Jesuit priest who the Darrell family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or 'The Smuggler', which depicts the 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell, who staged his own burial by filling a coffin with stones (a discovery made years later when his coffin was excavated).
The darrells are Rhodes' favourite family of Scotney: "The lords seemed to be quite a crook, repeatedly debt and spend money on things they could not afford.
Other generations of Darrell men resolved their debt crises by marrying rich old women - I imagine them as a bunch of handsome boys, with a talent to recruit heirs. "
After the end of his mission to the castle, Rhodes is in search of other unique writing experiences.
He has spent two weeks in the Finnish wilderness for a comic novel about Elämänmäki, the site of an early 20th century sanatorium that has since been reclaimed by nature.
But Scotney has a special place for him.
"I was sad to go back," he says.
It was like: 'Oh, now I have to deal with the damned life again'.
