Military reform in Turkey - Erdogan's Fear of the Army
Every year at the beginning of August in Ankara the Supreme Military Council (YAS) advises on retirements and promotions in the officer corps.
This week.
At first glance a normal procedure.
But nothing is routine with the Turkish armed forces one year after the coup attempt.
The sitting was no longer held in the General Staff building, as was the case in the past, but in the Prime Minister's office.
Under the leadership of the Heads of State or Government, the five Vice-Premier and the Ministers for Defence, Home Affairs, Justice and Foreign Affairs also took part in the discussions.
As a result, the number of civilians in the YAS was higher.
The government is taking the reins in the military.
Chief of Staff, Hulusi Akar, remains in office, but the commanders of the army, the air forces, and the navy have been deposed.
Since the failed coup, Erdoğan has fired 169 of the 326 generals and admirals.
More than 10,000 soldiers have been removed from the army ’ s ranks, mostly because of alleged ties to the movement of Fethullah Gülen, whom Erdogan sees as the mastermind of the coup attempt.
There have been some 486 people who are said to have been directly involved in the coup attempt in Ankara since this week.
The day after the coup, Erdogan had already called the coup attempt a "gift of God," giving him the opportunity to "clean up" the armed forces completely.
But is Erdogan really in control of the army??
At the end of February the newspaper "Hürriyet" published an article entitled "Uneasiness at Military Headquarters".
In the General Staff there were concerns about an increasing "Islamisation" of the army, which is manifested, among other things, in the lifting of the ban on headscarves for female soldiers, wrote the newspaper.
The wholesale cleaning up of the army and the security forces is continuing.
In mid-July, Erdoğan issued a decree to fire another 7395 civil servants, including 2303 police officers and 546 soldiers.
Erdoğan seemed to have tamed the military.
The generals used to be the actual masters of the country.
They fought three times, invoking their role as guardians of the secular order of state.
Following his election victory in 2002, Erdogan gradually pushed back the power of the military, not least on the basis of the European Union ’ s reform requirements.
Former officers say that Erdogan is pursuing a targeted Islamization of the armed forces.
In the 'Vocal Europe' magazine, a nameless officer who sought asylum abroad for fear of persecution after the coup attempt warned that in a few years' time the Turkish army would be 'full of extremists and Salafists'.
If so, such a development could not leave NATO cold.
In any case, after the purges, the Alliance has doubts about the commitment of the Turkish army.
NATO diplomats say that leadership structures and operational capabilities are 'weakened'.
