Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate could help to relieve IBD (inflammatory bowel disease)
Red meat and chocolate can sound like a nightmare for your digestive system.
But a new study claims exactly the opposite: a diet rich in meat-based proteins and dairy products could relieve the symptoms of patients with inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable state of affairs, which affects around 1.3 million in the United States and 300,000 in the United Kingdom, causes stomach cramps and bulges, recurrent or bloody diarrhoea, loss of weight and extreme fatigue.
While those affected are usually advised to avoid meat and dairy products to relieve their symptoms, researchers at Washington University found that the essential amino acid tryptophan of proteins helps to develop immune cells that promote tolerant intestines.
The chief researcher, Dr. Marco Colonna, explained that immune cells are patrolling the intestines to ensure that harmful microbes hiding in food do not penetrate the body.
Cells capable of triggering inflammation are compensated by cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance tends too far towards inflammation, it may result in inflammatory bowel disease.
Experiments found that a kind of tolerant immune cell occurs in mice carrying a particular bacterium in their bowels.
And the bacterium requires tryptophan - one of the building blocks of proteins - to trigger the appearance of the cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We have established a link between a bacterial species - lactobacillus reuteri - which is a normal part of the intestinal microbiotim, and the development of a population of cells that promote tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their food, the more they had of these immune cells.
He suggested that the combination of L. reuteri and a diet rich in tryptophan promotes a more tolerant, less inflammatory intestinal environment when the same system also affects humans.
The postdoctoral Dr. Luisa Cervantes arragan investigated a kind of immune cell that promotes tolerance when she found that a group of study mice had such cells, but another group of the same tribe, which was separated, had not.
She suspected that the difference had to do with the intestinal microorganisms of the mice - the community of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The mice ’ dams were DNA sequenced, and six bacteria strains were found that were present in mice with the immune cells, but were absent from mice.
mice were raised in a sterile environment, so they lacked a intestinal microbiotim and they did not develop this type of immune cells, and they were given the L. reuteri and the immune cells.
To understand how the bacteria had an impact on the immune system, researchers allowed L. reuteri to grow in a liquid and then transferred small quantities of the liquid - without the bacteria - to immature immune cells isolated from the mice.
The immune cells became the tolerant cells.
When the active component was purified from the liquid, it proved to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism known as indol 3 lactic acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in mice feed, the number of such cells increased by about 50%, but when tryptophane values were halved, the number of cells fell by half.
Dr. Cervantes Baragan explained that humans have the same tolerant cells as mice, and that most of us protect L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether tryptophan derivatives from L. reuteri develop the cells in humans as they do in mice, but defects in genes related to tryptophan have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
She said: "The development of these cells is probably something we want to promote, as these cells control inflammation on the inner surface of the intestine.
Potentially, high levels of tryptophane in the presence of L. reuteri can lead to an expansion of this population. "
