The White House ’ s decision to fly a naval helicopter to the South Lawn for an event that highlighted American manufacturing last month costs taxpayers up to $24,000, according to the military that was handed over to the TIME magazine.
The green-white Sikorsky VH-3D, known as Marine One when the president is on board, was the heart of the event on July 17 at the White House with American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence, and senior White House officials made a tour of products from all 50 countries.
The helicopter, manufactured in Connecticut, was exhibited next to a Maine yacht, a Wisconsin fire brigade car, and a Mississippi forklift.
The White House Military Office demanded the presence of the helicopter in a fragmentary order or FRAGO, barely 36 hours before the helicopter landed on South Lawn, according to the records of the Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1), the unit responsible for the operation of the helicopter.
"I just wanted you to be aware of this because it is such an unusual event with high visibility," wrote the commander of the HMX-1 on the eve of the event his boss, the deputy naval commander for aviation.
The news indicated that the helicopter arrived at South Lawn at 3 p.m. on 17 July at 7 a.m. for the event, and that it remained until the grass was cleared from 6 p.m. to 9 p.m. this evening.
The note adds that if departure from the White House were to be delayed, a second team would be required for the return flight due to the restrictions on working hours.
The original flight crew was on the helicopter during the event, while the security personnel of the unit remained on the ground during the time.
It was not clear from the records made available to the TIME whether a second flight crew was ultimately required.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using state property for political purposes.
Data records indicate that HMMX-1 asked if the event could break the determination.
"One question we asked was whether it was a violation of the Hatch Act and we were informed that this was not the case," wrote the commander.
"Sounds as if you were closed," replied the Deputy Commander.
The Made in America event was called an official event by the White House and would not have been covered by the Hatch Act.
But official events also have political overtones.
At the event, the president gave impetus to reform the health reform that was underway in the Senate, and he promoted efforts to contain government regulations.
The use of the aircraft known as Marine One or Air Force One for politically advantageous purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are obliged to use them for the trip.
But to request their use only for a photo op is unusual.
Trump conducted an investigation in February, when the presidential plane offered taxi services against the backdrop of his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account is full of complaints about his predecessor ’ s use of the presidential plane.
"The White House is thrilled by the show" Made In America "- showing products from all 50 countries made by American workers with American materials," said the White House Deputy Secretary of the Press, Lindsay Walters.
HMS 1 crews often carry out training flights around Washington and South Lawn to sell the US president to the White House with precise centimetres.
