Afghan democracy depends on the political role of women, says the UN.
Elections can only be representative if all members of society, including women, play a role, said the head of the UN mission in Afghanistan on Wednesday.
Nicholas Haysom, President-in-Office of the United Nations Mission, said that hundreds of women will stand in provincial elections, with three women standing for the role of Vice-President and more than 30% of newly registered voters being women.
"The role of women cannot be overestimated," he said in a statement on Wednesday.
Elections can only be truly representative and credible if women participate fully and are involved in all parts of the electoral process.
Afghan elections to the provincial council and presidential elections will take place on 5 April.
The Taliban have published threats against an electoral process that coincided with the transition from international fighting to an advisory role.
This year, for the first time, the elections will peacefully transfer power from one democratically elected government to another.
Haysom said that a strong role for women will enhance Afghanistan ’ s democratic success.
The Afghan Independent Electoral Commission reports that 1.2 million women are registered from a total of 3.6 million registered voters.
