GMB worries about investment in the McVitie factory in Glasgow
A trade union would like to check with managers of Biskup manufacturer McVitie the long-term commitment to production at its plant in Glasgow.
GMB Scotland said that the company had remained silent about the future of investments at the Tollcross site.
More than 500 employees work in the plant, which manufactures, among other products, Hobnobs and Rich Tea biscuits.
McVitie ’ s owner, Pladis, said he had invested more than £5 million in recent years.
He added that employees and trade union representatives would be "first experienced" if their activities changed.
In a letter to the company's branch manager, GMB Scotland asked McVitie's to "express concern that funding for the modernization of production lines would not be pushed forward".
GMB senior organizer Drew Duffy said: "The fact that we cannot get clarity from the General Site Manager about the business needs and investment plans for the future of Tollcross affects our members deeply.
Generations of families have worked here, and the workforce is heavily concentrated on the local community and the Greater Glasgow, an important pillar of decent employment in an area of high unemployment and social deprivation.
Thus, from the perspective of jobs, wages, and prosperity, and against the backdrop of Brexit, rising living costs, and chronic output decline, the eastern end of Glasgow urgently needs a thriving manufacturing presence at McVitie. "
A spokeswoman from Pladis said: "The managing director at Tollcross received a letter from GMB Scotland only yesterday, and the company will respond directly, as we appreciate the ongoing commitment of employees and trade union representatives.
Two months ago, we had a regular meeting with staff and GM representatives at Tollcross, where some issues were discussed openly.
We discussed with the staff that we, like all companies operating in a highly competitive and insecure economic climate, are constantly reviewing our business - and this applies to all our business areas and locations - in order to remain competitive.
She added: "In recent years, we have invested more than £5 million in our Tollcross site, particularly in production lines and operational improvements.
We fully recognise the legacy of Tollcross as a production site and, if our operations at the site change, the employees and their trade union representatives will be the first to know. '
