In an interview with the Bavarian Radio, Princess Gloria of Thurn und Taxis also said: "It is a pleasure to go to the church and that is a picnic".
She also pointed out that in her youth, 'blows were a normal pedagogical tool' to deal with naughty children, as I was one. '
They would find it unfair to apply today ’ s standards to earlier decades, because the world has changed.
In connection with the reports of cases of abuse, the Pope's brother Georg Ratzinger often appeared.
The author and historian Michael Hesemann, who wrote with Ratzinger the commemorative book "My Brother of the Pope" (translated into 12 languages) is completely wrong.
"I have to protect Georg Ratzinger," says Hesemann, "because all this had nothing to do with him," he assesses the results of the final report.
What exactly is stated in the 440 page report presented by the lawyer Ulrich Weber, who was appointed to investigate by the diocese of Regensburg?
A total of 547 Regensburg Cathedral Spatzen were sexually abused between 1945 and the beginning of the 1990s "with a high degree of plausibility".
The final report on Georg Ratzinger, who worked in Regensburg from 1964 to 1994, states: "In summary, it can be noted that in many cases Domkapellmeister R. used forms of physical and psychological violence.
Particularly with high emotionality, the punishment for the pupils could also be more severe.
However, in contrast to many other accused, it is striking that many victims appreciated the general humanity of R. and therefore in many cases even associate positive memories with him ".
In the interview, Hesemann explains why he considers the final report on the scandal of abuse to relieve Georg Ratzinger.
Mr Hesemann, the 440-page report on the "incidents of the use of force on protected persons in the Regensburg Cathedral Spatzen" gives a contradictory picture of the master master of the cathedral Georg Ratzinger.
On the one hand, many students highlight their "humanity".
On the other hand, he also appears as a cholera and perfectionist, who often became handy when a Domspatz musically did not deliver top performance.
How do you regard this final report as his biographer?
Michael Hesemann: If you take the trouble to read the whole 440 pages long report from the front to the back, you have to ask yourself why the name Georg Ratzinger actually appears in it.
Only eight pages are devoted to it and it is clearly cleared of any suspicion of complicity or complicity in the terrible cases of sexual abuse.
The excesses of violence at pre-school also occurred outside its sphere of effect.
At best, he can be accused of learning too late, or of not taking early hints seriously enough.
The Domspatzengymnasium on which he worked was perceived by virtually all respondents as - literally - "redemption", "heaven" and "better world".
The vast majority of his students, Georg Ratzinger, give excellent testimony, describing him as' warm ',' popular ',' honest ',' competent 'and' sympathetic ', a very kind teacher who regularly provided the boys with cakes, biscuits and sweets and was' always surrounded by grapes from children '.
Only a minority complained about his perfectionism and his high emotionality, which has already led to clashes.
He acknowledged, deeply regretted and apologised for the fact that he not only cracked with chairs and threw the keyring on the floor, but also drew ears and ears for overly cheeky boys.
In order to save his honour, however, it must be said that such educational methods were widespread in the period in question, the 1960s and 1970s, both among parents and among teachers.
Do you also know such breeding methods?
Of course, I think each of us who was born before 1968.
I, too, experienced this in a secular school, a state high school.
Compared to what this report is all about, namely the appalling sexual abuse and excessive violence at pre-school, these are, of course, trivial things.
One wonders if it is not his fame and role as the brother of Benedict XVI that many media have fallen upon him.
Many who have never understood him are still working diligently with the Bavarian Pope.
But the truth is: the report relieves Georg Ratzinger in every respect!
In connection with the report, a great deal has been reported in the media on the subject of abuse in the Regensburg Cathedral Spatzen.
Is Georg Ratzinger also accused in the final report of any involvement or complicity with regard to sexual abuse?
Michael Hesemann: Absolutely no.
Not one of the 67 victims of sexual assaults claims to have entrusted himself to the Cathedral Chapel Master.
Not even the parents were open.
"I never dared to talk to my father or mother about this," one person said on behalf of the others, "I was very embarrassed."
The real problem in educating about sexual abuse was, and still is, that most victims remain silent out of shame.
If they were not even entrusted to parents and siblings, it would certainly not have been a choir leader who, in a way, would have been a colleague of the perpetrators in his professional capacity.
How do you judge Ratzinger's role in the abuse cases?
Michael Hesemann: As one student put it: "Regarding sexual abuse... I don't see a case where he (Georg Ratzinger) would have had timely knowledge and could have stopped the perpetrator.
I think it is also really absurd to think that it is precisely him who... boys have opened up more intrusive, clearer or even earlier than their parents, head of boarding schools, confidence teachers, etc.
That you talk to him about sex... - unthinkable. '
The report thus comes to the very clear conclusion: 'The fact that pupils and / or their surroundings were entrusted to him in advance could not be confirmed in the context of the investigation'.
As far as sexual abuse is concerned, Georg Ratzinger is therefore free from any complicity.
In this way, he cannot be accused of not having prevented him or brought him to trial.
There is therefore no reason to associate his good name with these vile crimes, as has unfortunately happened in some cases.
There was a lot of talk in the media about "excesses of violence" in the Regensburg Cathedral Spatzen.
The former cathedral master Georg Ratzinger is accused in the report of "looking the other way".
Must he live with this accusation?
Michael Hesemann: This is the big problem that everything in the report has been mixed up and mixed up into a huge melange of sexual abuse and violence and somewhere, in the middle of it, Georg Ratzinger.
But that, again, is an abuse of the report.
There is a clear distinction between pre-school and high school, between sexual abuse and excessive violence and, let us say, other accusations.
In addition, the report deals with incidents since 1945, including four decades in which Georg Ratzinger was not a choral conductor of the Cathedral Spatzen.
All the terrible teaching of caning, the cases in which boys were really harassed and maltreated by sadistic teachers and suffered appalling, occurred at the preschool in Etterzhausen and Pielenhofen, where truly scandalous conditions must have prevailed.
But Georg Ratzinger, the master of the cathedral, had nothing to do with them, because he only saw the boys when they were already on the cathedral's gymnasium.
On this, as most witnesses emphasize, the theme "preschool" was taboo.
One was only happy to have escaped and enjoyed the much better treatment and, for many, even "paradise" conditions.
What was different on the Domspatzgymnasium?
Michael Hesemann: There was discipline, but no sadistic violence.
This also applies to Georg Ratzinger, where the report concludes that "many victims appreciated the general humanity of R. and therefore in many cases even combine positive memories with it despite violence".
At most, there is still a charge of looking the other way.
Despite all the efforts, however, the report has only been able to define two periods of time during which it was informed of conditions at pre-school.
The first time in 1970 / 71, when he was just beginning to establish himself and did not want to hear of the events at a school in which he was not active and responsible (according to the witness), and then only again in 1993.
Did Georg Ratzinger consistently close his ears to the situation?
Michael Hesemann: No, because as long ago as 1989 he wrote a letter to the director of the Cathedral Cemetery, which the report even reproduces.
He pointed out to them that 'caning continues to be practised in preschool'.
Even in view of the risk of negative press releases, he recommended urgent intervention.
This was, of course, at a time when legal clarity existed, when caning was banned long ago in Bavaria too.
Before that, they were in a legal grey area, as all of us still know.
It was also difficult for him to assess where the people concerned were perhaps exaggerated or dramatised and where the permissible limit had really been exceeded.
Nor can we say that he has always looked the other way.
That is simply not true.
It was not until 1980 that caning in schools was officially abolished in Bavaria.
After all, Princess Gloria of Thurn und Taxis claimed that it was unfair to apply today ’ s pedagogical standards to those days.
How do you see this?
Michael Hesemann: We historians talk about the "trap of anachronism", that is, the danger of judging the past according to today's moral standards.
The lady is quite right.
But this does not, of course, apply to sexual abuse, which was abhorrent at all times, nor to the atrocities committed against innocent children ’ s souls in pre-school, which goes far beyond what was then common.
That is all quite terrible and I am glad that it is finally being worked out.
But at the same time I have to protect Georg Ratzinger, because all this had nothing to do with him.
His means of disciplining and punishing, that is to say, pulling earlobes and ears, were widespread in the 1970s.
When corporal punishment was then banned, he also adhered strictly to it.
What image of his time in Regensburg did Georg Ratzinger present in the talks with you for the book "My Brother of the Pope"?
Did the topic of caning also come up?
Michael Hesemann: Well, the book is about the life of his brother Joseph, Pope Benedict XVI., tells from his perspective, since the parities played only a minor role.
Nevertheless, I do not at all hide the fact that he led a strict regime there.
But this must be said once again: without this perfectionism, without demanding unconditional discipline, he would hardly have been able to form an institution of world renown from the so far more nationally known Regensburg Cathedral Spatzen, true cultural ambassadors of Europe and his musical tradition, which went on tour twice in the USA (1983 and 1987) and Japan (1988 and 1991).
With biscuits and sweets alone, you don ’ t make the most of recalcitrant boys and you ’ ll face every success in any field, but always discipline, passion and self-overcoming.
As a human, did you experience Georg Ratzinger during the talks on her book?
Michael Hesemann: Through the work on the book and beyond, I have really got to know Georg Ratzinger very well and I have seen him again and again as wonderful, humourous, good-natured, deeply believing and good-natured people, of whom it is impossible to imagine that he could do anything for a fly.
I get to know on a regular basis how many former victims of the cathedral still have contact with him, visit him, read him - he is almost blind - and treat him as a member of their family, 23 years after his.
Those who still do not forgive him for being strict with them are clearly in a minority.
Today, most of the Domspats are grateful to him for enriching their lives and bringing the world of music to them.
And that he was always a good, fatherly teacher - a strict father, certainly, that may be - but also a loveable respecter, to whom they still look up today and who they almost worship.
And please, let us be clear once again: all that is being reproached is methods of education that were on the agenda at the time.
We can be glad that we have long since overcome this period.
But it is highly unjust to turn a man into a media scapegoat simply because he is prominent and has an even more prominent brother.
The evil intent behind this is all too obvious.
The report that has just been published relieves it.
Now, decency would dictate that a 93-year-old man who has earned himself great merit and without whom, outside Bavaria and perhaps even Germany, no one would know the Regensburg Cathedral Spatzen, finally be at peace.
